properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard possible Friday night into Saturday. A strong low pressure system will make its way through Hudson Bay toward southern Baffin Island on Friday. Heavy snow is expected to begin late Friday or early Saturday along with rapidly intensifying easterly winds. Current indications are for up to 10 cm of fresh snow accompanied at times with winds gusting to 80 km/h. At minimum, visibility reductions in blowing snow are expected for much of Saturday. Blizzard conditions will also be possible should the system continue on its current forecast track or intensify further. Conditions will improve late Saturday as the system moves off into Foxe Basin. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds, snow and blowing snow are expected Friday afternoon and evening. Southerly winds on Friday afternoon will become westerly in the wake of a strong cold front. Wind gusts of 70 to 80 km/h are expected beginning late in the afternoon on Friday. Winds are expected to diminish early on Saturday morning. Strong winds combined with falling snow will result in blowing snow. Expect visibilities to be significantly reduced, particularly late in the afternoon and into the evening on Friday. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Temperatures will rapidly fall with the passage of the cold front on Friday night. Wind chill values near -40 are expected by Saturday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Coastal flood warning issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec Region on 2020-12-17. Higher than normal water levels and waves are expected near the coast this evening. A strong area of high pressure will bring moderate northeasterly winds to the region mentioned below. The combination of these winds and the fact that we are currently in a period of high amplitude tidal range could cause minor flooding along the coast near these localities, on the dates and at the times specified (Eastern Standard Time). Quebec City: 2020-12-17, from 06:30 p.m. to 09:30 p.m. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
